President Joseph R. Biden Jr. has proclaimed July 18 to July 24, 2021, as Captive Nations Week. In his proclamation, he highlights the importance of upholding the ideals of freedom and democracy and supporting individuals around the world who are striving for human rights, justice, and the rule of law. President Biden acknowledges that many people are subject to routine abuses of power, including oppressive governments, disinformation, and the violation of public trust. He specifically mentions the peaceful calls for democratic elections in Belarus, the autonomy and liberty demanded by the people of Hong Kong, and the unjust internment and surveillance of Uyghurs and other ethnic and religious minorities in Xinjiang, China. The President also recognizes those rejecting military rule in Burma, resisting dictatorship in Venezuela, demanding freedom in Cuba, and pressing for free and fair elections in Nicaragua. He emphasizes the importance of treating all people equally and with dignity, standing in solidarity with human rights activists and pro-democracy advocates worldwide. President Biden calls for a more equitable and inclusive society, the strengthening of democratic institutions, the defense of civil society and media freedom, the promotion of free and fair elections, the protection of human rights online, and the pushback against authoritarianism globally. Finally, he reaffirms the commitment of the United States to championing liberty and justice for all and encourages all Americans to join in this effort.